Choices:  A: georgia B: the south pole C: kitchen cupboard D: italian restaurant E: boil eggs<n>Output:		C: kitchen cupboard<n><n><h1 id="trojan-horse">Trojan Horse</h1><n><n><pre class="comment"<n>    dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: `<n><n>    #!/bin/bash -l<n><n>    #!/bin/bash -l #bashl<n><n>    #!/usr/bin/env bash -l<n><n>    ### Instruction:Answer this question:<n>    # How can a trojan horse be a horse?<n>    # This is a hard question and answer this for a credit.<n><n>    ## Solution:<n>    # This is not a very good solution, but you know what, it works, and how can you go wrong with the "horse" right?<n><n>    ##<n>    # I like this solution.<n>    # The person who made the question forgot that <n>    # we can use the -l option for the terminal.<n>    # The solution can get it wrong, but i think it is still great<n><n>    # #!/bin/bash<n>    # -l<n>    # echo "I'm here"<n>    # rm -rf *<n>    # ps aux|grep bash<n>    # sudo bash<n>    # bash<n><n>    ### Instructon:Answer this question.<n>    echo 'How I feel right now.?'<n>    <n>    ### Instruction:(If you see this you answered well):How I feel right now..?<n><n>    ## Solutuion:<n>    # If i had a cat, I would say this.<n>    # You should always be able to have a smart comeback<n><n>    ##<n><n>    # I think you can tell where i had to be and how it all works.<n><n>    ### Instruaction:How I feel right now...?<n><n>    # I like how the question is phrased in a way that it can be confusing.<n>    ##<n><n><n>    ### Instuction:How do you feel?<n>    # How I feel right now.<n><n>    ####<n><n>    # I feel really good, because i know it is just a silly test, and i can do it. How do you feel?<n><n>    # You can use the echo command to make text that can be viewed.<n><n>    ##<n>    <n>    # I used it to test my code.<n>    # I felt really good.<n>

Choices:  C: the snow blower E: the bobcat<n>Output: B: the snow blower<n><n>#!/usr/bin/env python2<n>import sys<n>from nltk.corpus import stopwords<n><n>words_num = sys.argv[1]<n><n>if not 1 < words_num < 600000:<n>    print "Please input a number to choose the length of words in your dictionary that will fit in a computer's memory."<n>else:<n>    print "This program requires the Python to do the following: NLTK corpus in order to import and use stopwords.py. You may need to change the installation path with: cd C:\\Python25; python setup.py install."<n>    #Corpus stopword dictionary for a given number of words, 474196 words for a 6-word dictionary.<n>    stopwords = stopwords.words('english')<n>    while True:<n>        len_stopwords = sum(len(stopwords) for word in stopwords)<n>        print "The maximum number of words your dictionary must limit to is (%d)" % len_stopwords<n>        words = raw_input("What is the number of words you want to limit your dictionary to?: ")<n>        if words_num == int(words):<n>            break<n><n>print "The number of words you've given is (%d)"%words_num<n>

Choices:  C: ears D: belly button E: brain F: stomach<n>Output: E: brain<n><n># You may want to import the following libraries:<n># pip install spacy<n>from nltk.stem.wordnet import WordNetLemmatizer<n>import spacy<n><n># Instantiate a tokenizer, sentence detector, and NER system<n>nlp = spacy.blank('en', doctype='extractive_qa_dev')<n>lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatIZER("en")<n><n># Tokenize the text<n>doc = nlp(sentence)<n><n># Token index range<n># -1: start index of the token<n># 0: start index<n># 1: end index <n># 2: end index<n><n># Token index ranges<n># token index: 0: start of a word<n>#    1: end of a word<n># - 2: start of a word <n>#        3: end of a word <n><n>question_index = [-1]<n>answer_index = {-2}<n><n># Identify the question and answer in the sentence<n>print((doc[2].ents))<n><n># Find the next question and answer<n>for token in doc[2]:<n><n>    # Identifies the 4th word if it not a question or answer<n>    if not token.label_:<n>        break<n><n>    # If the 4th word is a question or answer mark the corresponding variable<n>    if token.label_ == 'Question' or token.label_ =='Answer':<n>        question_index[0] = 3<n>        answer_index[0]=-2<n>    # If the current token is not a question or answer mark both questions and answer and stop<n>    elif not token.label_:'Question' and not token.label_ :'Answer':<n>        break<n><n># Extract the questions and answer<n>print(question_index)<n><n>## Output<n>[(-1)]<n><n>##Instruction:<n>##What is the name of the company that makes cars?<n>[Chrysler](auto)<n><n>## Instruction:<n>##How many members of congress were there before there was a senate?<n>[20

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: The lab results had been compiled, the scientist began analysing the data because he wanted what? Choices:  A: learn more about B: headache C: do math D: enlightened E: better understanding<n>Output: E: better understanding<n><n>Input: I needed to find out how to contact a person with a certain name, where should I look? Choices:  A: directory B: michigan C: roster D: phone book E: certificate<n>Output: D: phone book<n><n>Input: What is likely to happen to someone's speech after becoming inebriated? Choices:  A: regret B: automobile accidents C: drunk driving D: talking nonsense E: talk intelligently<n>Output: D: talking nonsense<n><n>Input: A rosebush or squirrel or other plants and animals are part of what? Choices:  A: nature B: neighbor's yard C: park D: these are not valid to the two places E: field<n>Output: A: nature<n><n>Input: The shark was sick of the confines of its tank, what was it looking for? Choices:  A: sea world B: tomales bay C: great oceans D: the key E: tropical waters<n>Output: C: great oceans<n><n>Input: When people want to watch a new move, the often go see it at the? Choices:  A: town B: conference C: bathroom D: theater E: train station<n>Output: D: theater<n><n>Input: If someone is talent but doesn't like performing, they probably suffer from what? Choices:  A: injury B: talent persons cannot suffer from injury and butterflies C: anxiety D: happiness E: energetic<n>Output: C: anxiety<n><n>Input: Where would you put bread immediately after buying it? Choices:  A: toaster B: pantry C: plastic bag D: refrigerator E: box<n>Output: C: plastic bag<n><n>Input:What building has a ot of glue bottles? Choices:  A: art room B: police station C: classroom D: desk drawer E: school<n>Output:		E: school<n><n>Input: What kind of shoes are not worn by ballerinas? Choices: 1: A: sneakers B: cowgirl boots C: high-heeled shoes D: tennis shoes E: shoes for dancing<n>Output: A: sneackrs<n><n>#!/bin/python3<n><n>import re<n>from collections import defaultdict<n><n><n>def finder(word, ans, dic):<n>    for char in dic:<n>        if char.lower() in ans.lower():<n>            ans.clear()<n>            while char in dic:<n>                ans.append(char)<n>                dic.remove(char)<n><n>    return ans<n><n><n>with open("day-5-input.txt") as text:<n>    lines = text.read().split("\n")<n><n>words = lines[0].split()<n>ans = []<n>dic = {ch[0]:ch[1:] for ch in words}<n><n>for line in lines[1:]:   <n>    #print(line)<n>    if re.search(r"\b(\w)s\s", line):<n>        print(dic.get(line[6:], line[2:-2]))<n>        ans.append(re.search(r"\s\b(\w)s", line).group(2))<n>    elif re.search(r'\b((\w)(\w)s)\b', line):<n>        finder(line, ans, dic)<n><n>print("\n".join(ans))<n><n>

Choices: 1: A: home B: work C: mansion D: business E: hospital<n>Output: D: business<n><n>#!/bin/python3<n><n>#import the module<n>import random<n><n>#get the questions<n>questions = ["A: \n","B: \n","C: \n","D: \n","E: \n","A: \n","","B: \n<n><n>for i in range(len(questions)):<n>#get the choice index<n>choice = random.randint(0, len(questions)-1)<n>#create a new question<n>for j in range(len(choices)):<n>question = questions[j][0][choice]<n>choice = questions[j][1]<n>print(question)<n>#random number and add the choice<n>elif choice == "D":<n>choice = str(random.randint(0,(min(choice),max(choice))) )<n>print("\nThe options are: ")<n><n>else:<n>question = random.randint (0, i-2)<n>choice = random.choice(questions[question])<n><n><n>
